posts.name: mikets
posts.cooked:
As the season is starting, we are prep’ing our source tree by duplicating last year’s code and removing any season-specific stuff. But when deploying this skeleton code to the robot, all we see in the RioLog is: image 852×1116 10.1 KB We didn’t see any exceptions. It seems the robot code did not load and it kept doing it over and over again. BTW, we have the latest WPILib installed and the RoboRio with the latest image. At first, we thought it’s our code but I just tried “create a new project” either a Timed Robot Skeleton or a RobotBase skeleton, it’s the same result. So, it’s not our code. Any quick suggestions before I dive into debugging this? I searched past postings and found one two years ago but one major difference was they had an exception loading the robot code and we don’t see any. Peter Johnston replied that post about build.properties being wrong. But there is no such file in our project. I think it’s because we changed over to gradle build. I checked gradle.build and it is pointing to the correct robot MAIN object. BTW, we identified this output was printed by the code in RobotBase.java.

image 852×1116 10.1 KB

image 852×1116 10.1 KB

posts.name: mikets
posts.cooked: I lied about having the latest WPILib. Just found out there is a new release 2023.2.1 from yesterday. Will try to install that and check again. But I doubt that would change anything because the release note did not mention our problem.

Strange. Seeing the “** Robot program starting…” message indeed means that something based on RobotBase is created and started. In case of an error, you should see a stack trace, unless you somehow end up calling System.exit(..) to simply quit without error, but unclear how that would happen with the RobotBase skeleton.

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
There may be two issues in play here.

If you get about 50 or 100 or more repeated messages (they usually stop repeating soon with new messages arriving) that could be an issue that I reported long ago but I haven’t figured out what triggers it.

Then the other problem is your robotInit didn’t complete and likely didn’t print any more messages. Add some print() statements and maybe a flush() to track down which line of code is not working right.

posts.name: Thad House
posts.cooked: Can you try one of the normal templates, like TimedRobot? The RobotBase template isn’t designed to be normally used. And it’s possible there’s a bug in there causing an infinite crash loop. It’s never really tested.

posts.name: mikets
posts.cooked: Yes, I did try the TimedRobot template and it’s the same result, just never ending “Robot program staring …”. TimedRobot extends IterativeRobot which extends RobotBase at the end so I would think that should be the same.

posts.name: Thad House
posts.cooked: Ok. Also reading above, No communication means no rio log messages will occur, which might explain some of the issues. Without communication to the rio, everything we do is going to be pointless. Is it always no communication? If so is your firewall disabled completely (All 3 types, private public and domain). And I’m thinking something might be slightly broken in the rio image, so can you completely reimage your rio as well?

posts.name: Joe Ross
posts.cooked:

posts.name: mikets
posts.cooked: Interesting. Turning off all firewalls does work. Is this something new this season? I don’t recall having to turn firewalls off in the past seasons. Doesn’t that make my laptop vulnerable? What does turning off firewalls do? Allowing some ports on my laptop to be opened?

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked:
Vulnerable on untrusted networks (like public wifi. Definitely turn it back on before connecting to those networks), but the robot/field network is isolated, so it’s fine.

It’s definitely not “new”.  Us CSA’s and other field staff have been turning off firewalls on team DS laptops for years.  Step one of troubleshooting connectivity issues on the field is to check/disable the firewall.  That said, it doesn’t seem to be a global “hard” requirement for some reason.
